'''Tim Jackman''' (born November 14, 1981) is an [[United States|American]] professional [[ice hockey]] player, currently playing for the [[Calgary Flames]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL).  He was the first player from [[Minnesota State University, Mankato]] to be drafted after becoming the [[Columbus Blue Jackets]]' second round selection, 38th overall, at the [[2001 NHL Entry Draft]].  Jackman made his NHL debut during the [[2003<U+2013>04 NHL season|2003<U+2013>04 season]] with Columbus, and has also played for the [[Phoenix Coyotes]], [[Los Angeles Kings]] and [[New York Islanders]].

==Playing career==
Jackman attended Park Center High School in [[Brooklyn Park, Minnesota]], where he earned all-conference honors in 1998<U+2013>99 and 1999<U+2013>00, also earning all-state honors in the latter season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://forecaster.thehockeynews.com/hockeynews/hockey/player.cgi?2508 |title=Tim Jackman profile |work=The Hockey News |accessdate=2011-08-13}}</ref> He then attended [[Minnesota State University, Mankato]] for two seasons between  2000 and 2002.  A second-round selection of the [[Columbus Blue Jackets]], 38th overall in the [[2001 NHL Entry Draft]], Jackman became the first player from MSU-Mankato to be [[NHL Entry Draft|drafted]] by an NHL team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theahl.com/stats/player.php?id=332 |title=Tim Jackman player card |publisher=American Hockey League |accessdate=2011-08-13}}</ref> Jackman chose to forgo his final two years of college eligibility, signing a contract with the Blue Jackets in the summer of 2002,<ref>{{cite web |last=Milewski |first=Todd D. |url=http://www.uscho.com/2002/07/03/mankatos-jackman-signs-with-columbus/ |title=Mankato's Jackman signs with Columbus |publisher=U. S. College Hockey Online |date=2002-07-03 |accessdate=2011-08-13}}</ref> and went on to become the school's first alumnus to play in the NHL.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.msumavericks.com/sports/2010/10/1/MHOCKEY_1001103338.aspx?path=mhockey |title=2010<U+2013>11 Minnesota State Mavericks Media Guide |publisher=Minnesota State University <U+2013> Mankato |year=2010 |page=60}}</ref>

Jackman was assigned to Columbus' [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) affiliate, the [[Syracuse Crunch]] for the [[2002<U+2013>03 AHL season|2002<U+2013>03 season]].  He appeared in 77 games for the Crunch, scoring 9 goals and 16 points.<ref name="201011MGBio">{{Cite book |title=2010<U+2013>11 Calgary Flames Media Guide |publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club |last=Hanlon |first=Peter |last2=Kelso |first2=Sean |year=2010 |page=60}}</ref>  He spent the majority of the [[2003<U+2013>04 AHL season|2003<U+2013>04 season]] with Syracuse, scoring 23 goals in 64 games, but spent some time with Columbus.<ref name="201011MGBio" />  He made his NHL debut on December 20, 2003, in a game against the [[Minnesota Wild]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nhl/recap?gameId=231220030 |title=Minnesota unbeaten in past five games |publisher=ESPN |date=2003-12-20 |accessdate=2011-08-14}}</ref> and scored his first goal, assist and points on February 27, 2004, in a 4<U+2013>3 victory over the [[Chicago Blackhawks]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nhl/recap?gameId=240227004 |title=Richardson scores first goal in 183 games |publisher=ESPN |date=2004-02-27 |accessdate=2011-08-14}}</ref>

Following a third season with Columbus in [[2004<U+2013>05 AHL season|2004<U+2013>05]], Jackman was traded to the [[Phoenix Coyotes]] on October 8, 2005. He went to Phoenix with [[Geoff Sanderson]] in exchange for [[Cale Hulse]], [[Jason Chimera]] and [[Mike Rupp]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=nhl&id=2361786 |title=Phoenix Coyotes make flurry of trade deadline deals | publisher =ESPN | date = 2006-03-09 | accessdate = 2009-01-29}}</ref> He appeared in eight games with the Coyotes, but spent the majority of the 2005<U+2013>06 season with the AHL's [[San Antonio Rampage]].  Late that same season, on March 9, 2006, he was again traded, to the [[Los Angeles Kings]] for [[Yanick Lehoux]].  Jackman finished the season in the AHL with the [[Manchester Monarchs]].<ref name="LOH">{{cite web |url=http://www.legendsofhockey.net/LegendsOfHockey/jsp/SearchPlayer.jsp?player=20152 |title=Tim Jackman profile |publisher=Hockey Hall of Fame |accessdate=2011-08-13}}</ref>

Jackman played most of the [[2006<U+2013>07 AHL season]] in Manchester, appearing in only five games with Los Angeles.  He left the Kings organization following the season as a free agent, signing a contract with the [[New York Islanders]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.norwalkplus.com/nwk/information/nwsnwk/publish/Local_2/Islanders_sign_Tim_Jackman333.shtml|title=Islanders sign Tim Jackman | publisher =norwalkplus.com | date = 2007-07-08 | accessdate = 2009-01-29}}</ref>  He split time between the Islanders and the [[Bridgeport Sound Tigers]], scoring 1 goal in 36 NHL games and 15 in 44 AHL games.<ref name="LOH" />  Jackman finally established himself as an NHL regular in [[2008<U+2013>09 NHL season|2008<U+2013>09]], appearing in 69 games with New York, scoring 5 goals and 12 points.  He led the team in [[penalty (ice hockey)|penalty minutes]] and [[Checking (ice hockey)|hits]] with 155 and 151 respectively,<ref name="201011MGBio" /> and was named the recipient of the [[Bob Nystrom]] Award, and Islanders team award given to the player who beset demonstrates leadership, hustle and dedication.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://islanders.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=466255 |title=Jackman Wins Bob Nystrom Award |publisher=New York Islanders Hockey Club |date=2009-04-04 |accessdate=2011-08-13}}</ref> Jackman again led the Islanders in penalty minutes in [[2009<U+2013>10 NHL season|2009<U+2013>10]] with 98,<ref name="201011MGBio" /> and celebrated his birthday on November 14, 2009, by scoring a goal 16 seconds into the contest against the [[Florida Panthers]]. According to the [[Elias Sports Bureau]] it was the fastest goal in NHL history by a player on his birthday.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://espn.go.com/espn/elias?date=20091114 |title =Elias says.. |publisher=ESPN |date=2009-11-14| accessdate=2009-11-14 }}</ref>

Jackman left the Islanders after the season, signing with the [[Calgary Flames]].  He was brought in to bring a physical presence to the Flames lineup, but added an offensive presence for the Flames while playing in a limited role.  He scored a career-high 10 goals during the [[2010<U+2013>11 NHL season]], only one shy of his career total entering the season.<ref>{{cite news 
|last=Walker |first=Ian |url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:t-QZ9XjyN-sJ:www.vancouversun.com/sports/Flames%2BJackman%2Bleague%2Bbest%2Bbang%2Bbuck/4427227/story.html |title=Flames<U+2019> Tim Jackman best NHL bang for the buck |work=Vancouver Sun |date=2011-03-11 |accessdate=2011-08-13}}</ref>  He was named recipient of the [[List of Calgary Flames award winners#J. R. "Bud" McCaig Award|J. R. "Bud" McCaig Award]], given to the Flames player who exhibit respect, courtesy and compassion.<ref>{{cite web 
|url=http://flames.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=557725 |title=Jackman receives J. R. McCaig Award |publisher=Calgary Flames Hockey Club |date=2011-03-30 |accessdate=2011-08-14}}</ref>

